body:
The problem basically boils down to the following. The original problem can be seen in https://github.com/sdroege/byte-slice-cast/issues/1#issuecomment-392331136

```rust
fn foo<T: AsRef<[u8]>>(slice: &T) -> &[u8] {
    slice.as_ref()
}

fn bar(slice: &[u8]) -> &[u8] {
    slice
}
```

When passed a `&[u8]`, both functions should be exactly the same but in practice they behave different with regards to borrowing behaviour:

This works with and without the additional & (which will become important later)
```rust
    let b = bar(&bar(&slice));
    let b = bar(bar(&slice));
```

This fails and the & before the inner foo is necessary
```rust
    let slice = [1, 2, 3, 4];

    // 13 |     let s = foo(&foo(&slice));
    //    |                  ^^^^^^^^^^^ - temporary value dropped here while still borrowed
    //    |                  |
    //    |                  temporary value does not live long enough

    let s = foo(&foo(&slice));
```

Without the & it fails differently and I'm not sure why. There is no `[u8]` anywhere, only references to `[u8]` and those are `Sized`
```rust
    // &[u8] is Sized and that's what it operates on, not [u8]. The return value is &[u8]
    // 13 |     let s = foo(foo(&slice));
    //    |             ^^^ `[u8]` does not have a constant size known at compile-time
    //    |
    //    = help: the trait `std::marker::Sized` is not implemented for `[u8]`

    let s = foo(foo(&slice));
```

CC @Manishearth
